  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "EXAMPLE: Despite these achievements, Kenya’s GHG inventory system continues to face technical, institutional, and capacity-related challenges that hinder its ability to generate timely, complete, and policy-relevant data. While the inventory covers all sectors and gases using the 2006 IPCC Guidelines, it relies heavily on Tier 1 methodologies and default emission factors, particularly in key categories such as stationary combustion, transport, livestock, and waste. Only a few LULUCF categories use Tier 3 methods or country-specific emission factors. The 2024 NID identified 31 key categories, yet only six employed higher-tier methods, falling short of ETF expectations for methodological improvement over time."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "CBIT 1 laid a solid foundation by formalizing CARP as a national MRV platform, developing QA/QC manuals and GHG inventory guides, creating a climate data hub, and piloting reporting in the energy and transport sectors. It also integrated climate indicators into national development planning. However, the Terminal Review found that QA/QC remains inconsistently applied, uncertainty analyses are not institutionalized, and data collection remains ad hoc, reliant on donor-funded consultants and limited EPA staff capacity. The system lacks real-time data flows or regular baseline updates."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "One of the most significant gaps identified in the BTR1 and CBIT 1 Terminal Review is the absence of institutionalized capacity for GHG projections and scenario modeling. While Kenya’s BTR1 provides projections (2022–2040) under Without Measures (WOM), With Measures (WM), and With Additional Measures (WAM) scenarios using the Low Emissions Analysis Platform (LEAP), the process is not embedded within institutions. The projections rely on outdated data and assumptions, are insufficiently disaggregated to link with NDC sectoral targets, and are not integrated into development or sectoral planning frameworks like the Medium-Term Development Policy (MTDPF) or national budgeting."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The NID and the Updated NDC (2021) further reinforce these challenges by emphasizing the need to improve methodologies and strengthen institutional arrangements for GHG data management. The NDC mitigation measures depend on accurately quantifying emissions reductions and tracking progress toward targets, something the current MRV system cannot fully support. The lack of a feedback loop between reporting and policymaking weakens the NDC’s role as a tool for climate action."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Institutional fragmentation also impedes progress. The EPA lacks the authority to enforce cross-sectoral data sharing, and ministries are not legally obligated to submit disaggregated data. While CBIT 1 supported draft Memoranda of Understanding and data templates, these have not yet been adopted at scale. Comprehensive data management laws and mandates are still lacking."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Finally, technical capacity remains uneven. While the EPA has a trained core team, sectoral agencies lack expertise and face high staff turnover. The system depends on external consultants, lacks country-specific emission factors, and does not maintain sectoral databases or uncertainty assessments, making transparency reporting centralized, fragile, and unsustainable. EXAMPLE END."
      }
    ]
  },
